"Krewer U., Liauw M.A., Ramakrishna M., Babu M.H., Raghavan K.V.","Pollution prevention through solvent selection and waste minimization",2002,"Industrial and Engineering Chemistry Research","41","18",,"4534","4542",,,,"http://www.scopus.com/inward/record.url?eid=2-s2.0-0037019518&partnerID=40&md5=34bae6284cb7c240c6525c63276160d6","Lehrstuhl fur Technische Chemie I, University of Erlangen-Nuremberg, 91058 Erlangen, Germany; Indian Institute of Chemical Technology, Uppal Road, Hyderabad 500007, India; Max-Planck-Institute for Dynamics of Complex Technical Systems, Germany","Krewer, U., Lehrstuhl fur Technische Chemie I, University of Erlangen-Nuremberg, 91058 Erlangen, Germany, Max-Planck-Institute for Dynamics of Complex Technical Systems, Germany; Liauw, M.A., Lehrstuhl fur Technische Chemie I, University of Erlangen-Nuremberg, 91058 Erlangen, Germany; Ramakrishna, M., Indian Institute of Chemical Technology, Uppal Road, Hyderabad 500007, India; Babu, M.H., Indian Institute of Chemical Technology, Uppal Road, Hyderabad 500007, India; Raghavan, K.V., Indian Institute of Chemical Technology, Uppal Road, Hyderabad 500007, India","To prevent pollution in chemical manufacturing processes, concepts respectively for solvent selection and waste minimization have been developed and improved. The first concept selects solvents for a given process that exhibit good environmental behavior in addition to good performance. For the performance test, relative and absolute solubility calculations of solvent-solute combinations are performed, and reactivity is estimated. The acceptable solvents are tested for important environmental characteristics such as global warming, ozone depletion, risk of fire and explosion, BOD5, and toxicity. Estimations of the risk of fire and explosion were made by implementing a model for solvent storage in the calculation of Dow's F&amp;E index. The second concept helps minimize waste during manufacturing. Steinbach's concept of the balance yield BA is slightly varied and set into software. Both concepts are applied via software to manufacturing processes for NMSM. They identify the solvent DMSO as the most suitable solvent for the new process and highlight the most productive process, as well as the weak points of each process.",,"Ozone depletion; Global warming; Ozone; Solvents; Toxicity; Pollution control; 1 methylamino 1 methylthio 2 nitroethylene; 1,1,1 trichloroethane; 1,2 dichloroethane; 2 butanone; 2 ethylhexanol; 2 propanol; acetone; alcohol; benzene; butanol; dimethyl sulfoxide; ethylene derivative; hexane; hexanoic acid; methanol; propylene glycol; ranitidine; toluene; unclassified drug; water; xylene; environmental impact; materials selection; solvent; waste reduction; article; calculation; chemical analysis; chemical environment; chemical reaction kinetics; computer program; concept formation; greenhouse effect; materials; ozone layer; pollution control; process design; process optimization; solubility; task performance; waste minimization",,"1,1,1 trichloroethane, 71-55-6; 1,2 dichloroethane, 107-06-2; 2 butanone, 78-93-3; 2 ethylhexanol, 104-76-7; 2 propanol, 67-63-0; acetone, 67-64-1; alcohol, 64-17-5; benzene, 71-43-2; butanol, 35296-72-1, 71-36-3; dimethyl sulfoxide, 67-68-5; hexane, 110-54-3; hexanoic acid, 142-62-1, 151-33-7; methanol, 67-56-1; propylene glycol, 57-55-6; ranitidine, 66357-35-5, 66357-59-3; toluene, 108-88-3; water, 7732-18-5; xylene, 1330-20-7",,,,"Treweek, J., (1999) Ecological Impact Assessment, , Blackwell Science: London; Phillips, P.S., Gronow, B., Read, A.D., A regional perspective on waste minimisation a case study of the east midlands of England (1998) Resour. Conserv. Recycl., 23, pp. 127-161; Klimont, Z., Streets, D.G., Gupta, S., Cofala, J., Lixin, F., Ichikawa, Y., Anthropogenic emissions of non-methane volatile organic compounds in China (2002) Atm. Environ., 36, pp. 1309-1322; Bernardes, C., Industrial solid waste in the Sao Paolo metropolitan region-situation an